Participation of Emergent Bilinguals in the United States -- t12. English Learning without English Teachers? The Rights and Access of Rural Secondary Students in Nicaragua -- tAfterword -- tAppendix -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume explores the concept of 'citizenship', and argues that it should be understood both as a process of becoming and the ability to participate fully, rather than as a status that can be inherited, acquired, or achieved. From a courtroom in Bulawayo to a nursery in Birmingham, the authors use local contexts to foreground how the vulnerable, particularly those from minority language backgrounds, continue to be excluded, whilst offering a powerful demonstration of the potential for change offered by individual agency, resistance and struggle. In addressing questions such as 'under what local conditions does "dis-citizenship" happen?'; 'what role do language policies and pedagogic practices play?' and 'what kinds of margins and borders keep humans from fully participating'? The chapters in this volume shift the debate away from visas and passports to more uncertain and contested spaces of interpretation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCitizenship. 0aLanguage and languagesxPolitical aspects. 0aLanguage policy. 0aLinguistic minoritiesxCivil rights. 0aLinguistic minoritiesxEducation. 0aLinguistic minoritiesxGovernment policy. 0aNationalism. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Sociolinguistics.2bisacsh1 aCoelho, Fabio Oliveira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuran, Chatwara Suwannamai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeuerherm, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular